<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Decode the Hierarchy Through Label Geography</strong> - White Burgundy's quality pyramid is geographically encoded on the label. Village wines like Meursault or Puligny-Montrachet offer exceptional value and showcase classic buttery, mineral-driven Chardonnay character. Premier Cru vineyards (like Meursault "Perrières" or Chablis "Montmains") add complexity and aging potential. Grand Cru sites (Montrachet, Corton-Charlemagne) represent the pinnacle but require patience—they need 8-15 years to show their true magnificence.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Cooler Than You Think, Then Let It Warm</strong> - Start white Burgundy at 48-50°F (9-10°C), significantly cooler than most white wines. As it warms in the glass to 55-58°F, the wine's trademark mineral backbone softens and the subtle oak integration becomes more apparent. This temperature evolution reveals why great white Burgundy improves over 30-45 minutes in the glass—you're experiencing the wine's complete aromatic and textural spectrum.</li>

  <li><strong>Young Premier and Grand Crus Need Air</strong> - Contrary to popular belief, young white Burgundies (under 7 years) from Premier and Grand Cru sites benefit from 30-60 minutes of decanting. The reductive winemaking style used by top producers creates sulfur compounds that blow off with aeration, revealing the wine's true fruit and mineral character. Older wines (10+ years) should be opened and served immediately to preserve their delicate evolution.</li>

  <li><strong>Match Glass Shape to Wine Style</strong> - Chablis and Côte de Beaune whites require different glassware approaches. For mineral-driven Chablis, use a smaller bowl (like a Riedel Chablis glass) to concentrate the precise citrus and oyster shell aromas. For richer Côte de Beaune wines (Meursault, Chassagne-Montrachet), choose a larger Burgundy bowl that allows the complex hazelnut, butter, and tropical fruit notes to develop and integrate.</li>

  <li><strong>Understand the Village Vintage Sweet Spots</strong> - Village-level white Burgundies hit their drinking windows differently: Chablis peaks at 3-7 years when mineral tension balances fruit richness; Meursault shows best at 5-10 years when oak integration is complete; Puligny-Montrachet needs 4-8 years to develop its signature tension between power and elegance. Buy from excellent vintages like 2019, 2017, or 2014 for immediate pleasure, or 2020 and 2018 for cellaring.</li>

  <li><strong>Storage Position Matters More for White Burgundy</strong> - White Burgundy's high acidity makes it particularly sensitive to cork position during aging. Store bottles on their side in consistent 55°F conditions, but avoid excessive vibration—the wine's delicate lees integration can be disrupted. After 10+ years, check cork condition annually; white Burgundy's longevity depends entirely on cork integrity maintaining the wine's reductive environment.</li>

  <li><strong>Identify Producer Style Through Malolactic Fermentation</strong> - White Burgundy producers fall into two camps: those who encourage full malolactic fermentation (creating buttery, creamy textures) and those who block it partially (preserving crisp acidity). Domaine Leflaive and Louis Jadot represent the creamy style, while producers like William Fèvre in Chablis favor bright acidity. Understanding this helps predict how a wine will taste and age—high-malo wines peak earlier but age gracefully.</li>

  <li><strong>Pair with Fat and Umami, Not Just Seafood</strong> - White Burgundy's natural acidity and often-present malolactic richness make it perfect for umami-rich foods beyond the classic oysters. Try aged Comté cheese, roasted chicken with tarragon, or even pork dishes with mushroom sauces. The wine's mineral backbone cuts through rich fats while its subtle oak complements earthy flavors—this is why white Burgundy is the sommelier's secret weapon for challenging food pairings.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>White Burgundy's <strong>exceptional aging potential</strong> stems from its natural acidity, mineral backbone, and the Chardonnay grape's affinity for developing complex tertiary aromas. Understanding each quality level's evolution helps maximize your cellar investment.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Classification</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Bourgogne Blanc</strong>: 3-5 years, best consumed young for freshness</li>
<li><strong>Village wines</strong>: 5-8 years, developing honeyed complexity</li>
<li><strong>Premier Cru</strong>: 8-15 years, showing remarkable depth and minerality</li>
<li><strong>Grand Cru</strong>: 15-25+ years, with legendary examples aging gracefully for decades</li>
</ul>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>
<p>Young white Burgundy displays <strong>bright citrus and stone fruit</strong> with crisp acidity. As it matures, the wine develops layers of honeyed richness, toasted hazelnuts, and brioche from lees contact. The hallmark <strong>mineral tension</strong> intensifies, while fruit flavors evolve from fresh to dried and concentrated. Premier and Grand Cru wines develop extraordinary complexity—think truffle, wet limestone, and aged butter.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>
<p>Store bottles at <strong>55°F (13°C)</strong> with 70% humidity in complete darkness. Position bottles horizontally to keep corks moist. Vibration-free environments are crucial, as white Burgundy's delicate evolution can be disrupted by movement.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p>Most village wines hit their stride at <strong>4-6 years</strong>, while Premier Crus peak between <strong>8-12 years</strong>. Grand Crus often require patience—Montrachet and Corton-Charlemagne may need 10-15 years to fully express their terroir.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage</h3>
<p>Properly aged white Burgundy maintains <strong>bright acidity</strong> despite color deepening to golden amber. Warning signs include flat aromas, oxidized nutty smells without fruit balance, or brownish coloration. Premium cuvées should always retain that signature Burgundian tension between richness and minerality.</p>

