  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is white Burgundy good for beginners or too expensive to start with?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">White Burgundy offers excellent entry points through village-level wines from appellations like Saint-Aubin, Rully, or basic Bourgogne Blanc, typically ranging from $25-45. These wines showcase classic Burgundian Chardonnay character without the premium pricing of famous villages like Puligny-Montrachet. For beginners, start with a Chablis or Mâcon-Villages to understand the region's minerality and elegance before investing in premier cru bottlings.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long should I age white Burgundy before drinking?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Village-level white Burgundy can be enjoyed immediately but improves with 2-5 years of cellaring to develop complexity and integrate oak. Premier cru wines benefit from 5-10 years of aging, while grand cru bottlings like Montrachet can evolve beautifully for 15-20 years or more. The key is that white Burgundy develops tertiary aromas of honey, hazelnuts, and truffle with proper aging, transforming from primary fruit-driven wines into profound, complex expressions.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve white Burgundy at?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve white Burgundy at 50-55°F (10-13°C), slightly warmer than typical white wines to showcase its complexity and texture. Over-chilling masks the wine's subtle oak integration and mineral nuances that define quality Burgundian Chardonnay. Remove the bottle from the refrigerator 15-20 minutes before serving, and consider using larger Burgundy glasses to concentrate the wine's delicate aromatics.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good alternatives to expensive white Burgundy that taste similar?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for Chardonnay from cooler climates like Sonoma Coast, Tasmania, or Chabazanian-style wines from the Loire Valley's Sancerre producers who also make Chardonnay. Austrian Chardonnay from Wachau and quality German Weissburgunder (Pinot Blanc) can offer similar minerality and elegance. For the closest match, seek out Oregon Chardonnay from Willamette Valley producers who use Burgundian winemaking techniques with similar climate conditions.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How can I tell if a white Burgundy is made by a quality producer?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for producers who own their vineyards (domaine) rather than négociants who buy grapes, as evidenced by "Domaine" on the label followed by the family name. Quality indicators include hand-harvesting mentions, indigenous yeast fermentation, and restrained use of new oak (typically 20-30% for village wines). Research producers through wine publications or look for consistent vintage availability, as quality domaines maintain long-term relationships with importers.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying white Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is confusing appellation hierarchy with quality, assuming that a premier cru from an unknown producer will automatically be better than a village wine from a renowned domaine. Many buyers also overlook proper storage conditions, purchasing aged white Burgundy without knowing its provenance, which can result in premature oxidation. Additionally, drinking young grand cru wines immediately rather than allowing proper cellaring time wastes their aging potential and investment value.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why does white Burgundy vary so much in price between villages?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Pricing reflects historical reputation, vineyard classification, and terroir quality established over centuries of winemaking. Villages like Puligny-Montrachet and Chassagne-Montrachet command premium prices due to their grand cru vineyards and limestone-rich soils that produce exceptional wines. Lesser-known villages like Auxey-Duresses or Saint-Romain offer excellent value because they lack famous grand cru sites but often share similar geological conditions with their prestigious neighbors.</p>
  </div>
